d["body"] = "A Tirzah song at its most stripped down sounds like three elements held loosely together, her voice, a beat that barely arrives, and silence. The silence is doing something.\n\nTirzah Mastin is from Essex, England. She's been making music with producer Mica Levi for over a decade, and their collaboration defines her sound completely. Levi writes and produces everything. Tirzah sings over it. The result doesn't sound like either of them would make separately.\n\n[spotify:artist/6f5lOlSFJw9K79gaNnmWAd]\n\n*Devotion* (2018) was the first time most people heard her outside of small circles. Songs like \"Devotion\" and \"Fine Again\" used R&B as a starting point and then subtracted everything that made it recognizable. What's left is something skeletal and genuinely affecting. The production on those tracks sits so far back that the voice floats in near-empty space, and that emptiness is not absence. It is pressure. The restraint creates a tension that conventional production, with its layers and fills and movement, cannot replicate.\n\n## Colourgrade and After\n\n*Colourgrade* (2021) pushed further. There are moments on that record where the production almost collapses under its own weight, bass that flickers in and out, beats that stutter and restart, melodies that arrive late. It shouldn't work. It does. The album earned strong critical attention precisely because it operated so confidently in territory that most producers avoid, the space where a track might dissolve but holds.\n\nThe 2023 EP *trip9love...???* is even more abstracted. If *Devotion* was Tirzah finding her voice, *trip9love* is her testing whether voice is necessary at all. It's a short, strange record that rewards patience.\n\n## Mica Levi's Role\n\nLevi's production work outside this collaboration, the score for Under the Skin, the orchestral pieces, the film work, operates on similar principles. Levi understands that unease can be beautiful, that the wrong note held long enough becomes the right note, that production is not about filling space but about shaping it. What makes the Tirzah collaboration distinctive is how completely Levi's instincts and Tirzah's vocal character merge. There is no sense that the voice is being placed over a beat. There is a sense that voice and beat are a single organism with two components.\n\nThe fact that Levi writes and produces everything while Tirzah performs everything means the collaboration has a clarity of roles that prevents compromise. Neither party is adjusting to the other's preferences. They are building a shared language, and that language has been developing across multiple records into something increasingly coherent and increasingly strange.\n\n## The Question of Emotion\n\nWhat makes Tirzah's minimalism affecting rather than merely conceptually interesting is that the emotional content of the songs is not reduced by the stripped-back production. It is concentrated. When there are fewer sounds, each sound carries more weight. A single bass note holds grief that a conventional production might disperse across twenty tracks. A vocal line with nothing underneath it except sparse percussion becomes impossible to look away from.\n\nMost minimalist music in the experimental tradition treats emotion with suspicion, as if raw feeling were a contamination of the conceptual clarity being pursued. Tirzah's work treats emotion as the point. The minimalism is in service of the feeling, not a retreat from it. That inversion explains why her music reaches people who have no investment in experimental music as a category. They encounter it through the emotion first and discover the structure second.\n\nThe temptation for any producer working in this mode is to add things, to fill silences that feel uncomfortable, to provide the listener with more conventional signposts. Levi consistently refuses this temptation. The silences on a Tirzah record are not mistakes or omissions. They are decisions, and they are right.\n\n## What She's Building\n\nWhat she's building is a body of work that defies easy categorization. It's too abstract to be R&B, too rooted in emotion to be purely experimental. \"Do You Know\" from *Colourgrade* is probably the closest she gets to accessible, and it's still deeply strange, the rhythm section feels like it's tracking something other than a standard grid.\n\nShe doesn't do many interviews. She rarely performs. That distance from the promotional machinery feels intentional, and it fits the music. Mica Levi's production is similarly non-promotional, no radio-friendly mixes, no attempts to make the work go bigger than it wants to go.\n\n## The Entry Points\n\n\"Fine Again\" is the easiest starting point. \"Do You Know\" is the track that stays with you longest. \"trip9love\" the song is where you go once you need more, once the earlier work has calibrated your ears to what she is doing and you are ready for her to push that further.\n\nThere's a stubbornness to what she does that's increasingly rare. Making music this deliberately uncommercial, at this level of craft, without apology, represents a commitment to a specific vision that the industry does not reward and cannot manufacture. The audience for it is real and growing. That growth is happening on the music's terms, not anyone else's.\n\nShe and Levi have been working together since they were teenagers in the same music program. That duration of collaboration produces a shared understanding that no amount of professional rapport can replicate. They know what they are trying to do. They know how to tell when they have done it. The records they have made together are the evidence of that knowledge, accumulated across a decade of work that has never tried to be anything other than exactly what it is.\n\n## The Wider Context\n\nTimeline matters here. Tirzah and Levi began making music together before the streaming economy created a new set of pressures around release cadence and playlist placement. Their pace is deliberately slow. There have been three albums and two EPs across more than a decade of collaboration. That is not a career managed for visibility. It is a career managed for quality, or rather for something that sits underneath quality: the sense that the work was made when it was ready and not before.\n\nIn a moment when most artists are releasing material at quarterly intervals to stay algorithmically visible, the Tirzah catalog represents a conscious refusal of that logic. Each release arrives because there is something to say, and the space between releases is part of the statement. You cannot rush this kind of music into existence. If you try, you get something that sounds like it, which is not the same thing at all.\n\n[download:/assets/images/artists/tirzah-minimal-as-heartbeat-social-9x16.jpg|Download Social Card]"
